<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,685,711]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lang" authorityYear="1968" box="[429,611,685,710]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="12" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[429,611,685,710]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Carpoapseudes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, rostrum triangular, longer than eyelobe apophyses, with slight proximal shoulders; antennal flagellum of eight segments, antennular main flagellum of 25 to 26 segments, accessory flagellum (male) of nine segments; pereonite 6 without anterolateral spiniform apophyses. Male with auricular expansion on proximo-ventral margin of cheliped propodus, and dactylus with dorsodistal constriction at insertion of setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,885,911]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin 
<emphasis box="[537,602,885,910]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">varus</emphasis>
– bent, and 
<emphasis box="[753,816,885,910]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">index</emphasis>
– forefinger (noun in apposition), with reference to the constriction on the dactylus of the cheliped of the male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="12" pageNumber="25" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" box="[198,472,965,991]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,472,965,991]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Description of female.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[198,258,1005,1030]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Body</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[274,346,1005,1031]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="13.[151,254,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[220,1367,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-31@13.[177,1409,197,1968]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp. A, holotype, dorsal; B, holotype, lateral. Scale line = 2 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Dorsoventrally flattened, elongate, 
<typeStatus box="[783,885,1005,1031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">holotype</typeStatus>
<quantity box="[892,996,1005,1031]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.13" pageId="12" pageNumber="25" unit="mm" value="11.3">11.3 mm</quantity>
long (anterior tip of cephalon to posterior of pleotelson), seven times as long as wide, narrower posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[198,382,1085,1110]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Cephalothorax.</emphasis>
Sub-triangular, 0.9 times as long as wide, naked, anterior margin with rostrum, damaged in 
<typeStatus box="[184,287,1125,1151]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">holotype</typeStatus>
(see male, below). Eyes absent; eyelobes modified to prominent spine-like apophyses directed antero-laterally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[198,330,1205,1230]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Pereonites.</emphasis>
Pereonite 1 shortest, about one-third as long as cephalothorax, lateral margins uniformly convex. Pereonite 2 one-tenth as long again as pereonite 1 with slight anterolateral spiniform apophyses. Pereonites 3 to 5 with anterolateral spine-like apophyses, and expanded postero-laterally at attachment of coxae. Pereonite 3 1.5 times as long as pereonite 2. Pereonite 4 longest, 1.5 times as long as pereonite 3. Pereonite 5 0.8 times as long as pereonite 4. Pereonite 6 trapezoid, without lateral apophyses, as long as pereonite 2 (all pereonites respectively 3.2, 2.3, 1.4, 0.8, 0.9 and 1.8 times as wide as long). Ventral hyposphenia present on all pereonites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[198,274,1485,1510]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Pleon.</emphasis>
Just longer than pereonites 4 to 6 together, of five free subequal pleonites bearing pleopods. Pleonites 2.4 times as wide as long, laterally bearing spine-like apophyses.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" box="[198,1305,1565,1591]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[198,322,1565,1590]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Pleotelson</emphasis>
. Long and slender, as long as last four pleonites together, 2.4 times as long as wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[198,317,1605,1630]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Antennule</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[333,427,1605,1631]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="13.[151,254,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[220,1367,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-31@13.[177,1409,197,1968]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp. A, holotype, dorsal; B, holotype, lateral. Scale line = 2 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
). Peduncle 4-articled. Proximal article elongate, about ten times as long as wide. Second article 0.3 times as long as article 1 with distal crown of six setae. Third article just shorter than article 2. Fourth article 0.2 times as long as third article, naked. Main flagellum of 25 segments, articles 21 and 23 bearing single aesthetascs. Accessory flagellum incomplete.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[198,296,1765,1790]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Antenna</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[315,411,1765,1791]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="13.[151,254,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[220,1367,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-31@13.[177,1409,197,1968]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp. A, holotype, dorsal; B, holotype, lateral. Scale line = 2 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
). Proximal peduncle article without inner process. Article 2 naked, bearing elongate squama eight simple marginal setae. Peduncle article 3 as long as wide. Article 4 as long as article 1 and 1.5 times as long as article 5. Flagellum of eight segments.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,565,2031]" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[198,335,1885,1910]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="25">Mouthparts</emphasis>
not dissected. Small, naked epistome present. Mandibular palp of three articles, proximal article more than twice as long as wide, article 2 twice as long as article 1 with eight inner setae in the distal third, proximal seta longer than remainder, article 3 half length of article 2 with ten inner setae and two longer distal setae.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1255,1976,2000]" pageId="13" pageNumber="26" startId="13.[151,254,1976,2000]" targetBox="[220,1367,233,1951]" targetPageId="13">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1255,1976,2000]" box="[151,1255,1976,2000]" pageId="13" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,1976,2000]" pageId="13" pageNumber="26">FIGURE 7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Bamber, 2007" authorityName="Bamber" authorityYear="2007" box="[287,553,1977,2000]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="13" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varindex" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[287,553,1977,2000]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="26">Carpoapseudes varindex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[560,610,1977,2000]" pageId="13" pageNumber="26" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
A, holotype, dorsal; B, holotype, lateral. Scale line = 2 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption pageId="14" pageNumber="27" startId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" targetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" targetPageId="14">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1923,2015]" pageId="14" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,1923,1947]" pageId="14" pageNumber="27">FIGURE 8.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Bamber, 2007" authorityName="Bamber" authorityYear="2007" box="[287,553,1923,1946]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="14" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varindex" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[287,553,1923,1946]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="27">Carpoapseudes varindex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[559,612,1923,1946]" pageId="14" pageNumber="27" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,304,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Cheliped</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[320,413,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
). Basis twice as long as wide, ventrally with fine spine just distal of midpoint and distal tuft of eight setae. Exopodite present, 3-articled, second article naked, distal article with four plumose setae. Merus elongate with dorsal subdistal seta and ventral subdistal group of three longer and two shorter setae. Carpus 1.5 times as long as wide, expanding distally, with five simple setae along ventral margin, dorsodistal blunt apophysis with two adjacent simple setae. Chela slender, fingers longer than palm, ventral margin with four setae; two small setae near articulation of fixed finger; cutting edge of fixed finger with small, rounded proximal apophysis and row of setules and plate-like teeth (
<figureCitation box="[854,947,392,418]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
). Dactylus with sparse marginal setae but no apophyses on cutting edge (
<figureCitation box="[513,605,432,458]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
), shorter than fixed finger.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,334,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Pereopod 1</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[351,444,472,498]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="13.[151,254,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[220,1367,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-31@13.[177,1409,197,1968]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp. A, holotype, dorsal; B, holotype, lateral. Scale line = 2 mm." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[457,533,472,498]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">8B, D</figureCitation>
). With pronounced spine-like apophysis on coxa (
<figureCitation box="[1126,1199,472,498]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="13.[151,254,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[220,1367,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-31@13.[177,1409,197,1968]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp. A, holotype, dorsal; B, holotype, lateral. Scale line = 2 mm." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1212,1251,472,498]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">8D</figureCitation>
). Basis slender, 6.5 times as long as wide without proximal apophyses or spine. Exopodite present (
<figureCitation box="[1122,1215,512,538]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
), 3-articled, article 2 naked, article 3 with six distal plumose setae. Ischium with single simple ventrodistal seta. Merus with row of five ventral setae in distal half. Carpus longer than merus, with ventral row of marginal setae and dorsodistal tuft of four setae, longest of these as long as propodus. Propodus (
<figureCitation box="[952,1041,632,658]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
) shorter than merus and 3.4 times as long as wide, with nine slender dorsal setae and six ventral slender setae interspersed with five stouter spines. Dactylus short, less than half length of propodus, with mid-dorsal fine seta and four ventral denticulations; unguis short.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,335,792,817]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Pereopod 2</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[354,481,792,818]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 8E, F</figureCitation>
). More slender. Basis eight times as long as wide with one mid-dorsal and two ventrodistal setae. Merus 0.7 times as long as carpus, not widening distally. Carpus elongate, with ventral and dorsomedial rows of marginal setae. Propodus 0.8 times as long as carpus, with row of ventral marginal setae, sparser mid-dorsal marginal setae and dorsodistal tuft of five setae; single small ventrodistal compound spine. Dactylus slender with one mid-dorsal and one ventrodistal fine seta and three proximo-ventral denticulations; unguis slender, pointed, less than half length of dactylus, the two together longer than propodus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,404,1032,1057]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Pereopods 3 to 6</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[422,516,1032,1058]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="13.[151,254,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[220,1367,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-31@13.[177,1409,197,1968]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp. A, holotype, dorsal; B, holotype, lateral. Scale line = 2 mm." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
). Similar to pereopod 2, although pereopod 4 with denser tuft of dorsodistal setae on carpus. Pereopods 5 and 6 less setose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,307,1112,1137]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Pleopods</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[328,426,1112,1138]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[180,1397,187,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-85@14.[161,1426,162,1929]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp., A, female cheliped; B, distal articles of pereopod 1; C, detail of tips of chela fingers; D, coxa, proximal part of basis and exopodite of pereopod 1; E, pereopod 2; F, dactylus and unguis of pereopod 2; G, pleopod (plumose nature of setae not shown). Scale line = 1 mm for A, D, E and G, 0.3 mm for B, C and F." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 8G</figureCitation>
). All alike. Basis elongate with four outer and two inner plumose setae. Endopod shorter than exopod with proximal articulation; both rami slender, respectively with 17 and 16 plumose setae. Outer proximal seta on exopod sub-distally with robust setules, distally naked.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" box="[198,416,1232,1258]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,307,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Uropods.</emphasis>
Missing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" box="[198,1198,1271,1298]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,442,1271,1297]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Description of male</emphasis>
(only cephalothorax and associated appendages present: 
<figureCitation box="[1113,1184,1272,1298]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="16.[151,254,1654,1678]" captionTargetBox="[182,1391,196,1623]" captionTargetId="figure-148@16.[165,1422,177,1652]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 9. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp. A, male cephalothorax and appendages, lateral; B, outline of cephalon, ventral; C, distal detail of dactylus of cheliped. Scale line = 1 mm for A, B, 0.2 mm for C." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" box="[198,1304,1312,1338]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,321,1312,1337]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Carapace.</emphasis>
Rostrum triangular, longer than eyelobe apophyses, with slight proximal shoulders.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,317,1352,1377]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Antennule</emphasis>
main flagellum of 26 segments, most with paired aesthetascs. Accessory flagellum of nine segments.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" box="[198,660,1432,1458]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,296,1432,1457]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Antenna</emphasis>
with ten-segmented flagellum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis box="[198,304,1472,1497]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Cheliped</emphasis>
showing sexual dimorphism; chela fingers little longer than palm. Propodus with auricular expansion on proximo-ventral margin; fixed finger with two prominent proximal tooth-like apophyses on cutting edge. Dactylus with dorsodistal constriction at insertion of setae (
<figureCitation box="[970,1063,1552,1578]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="16.[151,254,1654,1678]" captionTargetBox="[182,1391,196,1623]" captionTargetId="figure-148@16.[165,1422,177,1652]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 9. Carpoapseudes varindex n.sp. A, male cephalothorax and appendages, lateral; B, outline of cephalon, ventral; C, distal detail of dactylus of cheliped. Scale line = 1 mm for A, B, 0.2 mm for C." pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,2018]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,1591,1617]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">Remarks.</emphasis>
The conformation of the rostrum (in the male), the antennular and antennal flagella and squama, and the pereonite proportions of the present species are all consistent with the description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lang" authorityYear="1968" box="[151,364,1672,1697]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serratispinosus">
<emphasis box="[151,364,1672,1697]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">C. serratispinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[410,560,1672,1698]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" pagination="23 - 209" refId="ref11576" refString="Lang, K. (1968) Deep-Sea Tanaidacea. Galathea Reports, 9, 23 - 209, Pl. I - X." type="journal article" year="1968">Lang (1968)</bibRefCitation>
. His detailed description related to the male; alas the present male lacks a body and all legs. Unlike Lang’s species, however, the rostrum has only slight proximal “shoulders”, and the cheliped does have an “auricular” expansion on the proximo-ventral margin of the cheliped propodus, as described for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bacescu" authorityYear="1981" box="[315,469,1792,1817]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kudinovae">
<emphasis box="[315,469,1792,1817]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">C. kudinovae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bacescu, M." box="[517,700,1792,1818]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" pagination="9 - 14" refId="ref10823" refString="Bacescu, M. (1981) Carpoapseudes kudinovae n. sp. in the French waters of the Atlantic. Revue Roumaine de Biologie, Serie de Biologie Animale, 26, 9 - 14." type="journal article" year="1981">Bãcescu (1981)</bibRefCitation>
, who states that this feature may be present in other species for which the fully mature male is undescribed; it is also found in 
<taxonomicName authority="Kudinova-Pasternak, 1975" authorityName="Kudinova-Pasternak" authorityYear="1975" box="[889,1381,1832,1858]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auritocheles">
<emphasis box="[889,1063,1832,1857]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">C. auritocheles</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kudinova-Pasternak, R. K." box="[1072,1381,1832,1858]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" pagination="682 - 687" refId="ref11469" refString="Kudinova-Pasternak, R. K. (1975) Tanaidacea (Malacostraca) of the deep-sea trench Romansh and Guinea Hollow. Zoologicheskii Zhurnal, 54, 682 - 687." type="journal article" year="1975">Kudinova-Pasternak, 1975</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Norman &amp; Stebbing, 1886)" baseAuthorityName="Norman &amp; Stebbing" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[151,680,1872,1898]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplicirostris">
<emphasis box="[151,347,1872,1897]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">C. simplicirostris</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Norman &amp; Stebbing T. R. R." box="[361,671,1872,1898]" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" pagination="77 - 141" refId="ref11905" refString="Norman A. M. &amp; Stebbing T. R. R. (1886) On the Crustacea Isopoda of the ' Lightning', ' Porcupine' and ' Valorous' Expeditions. Transactions of the Zoological Society of London, 12 (Part IV, No. 1), 77 - 141, Pls 16 - 27." type="journal article" year="1886">Norman &amp; Stebbing, 1886</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The present species is neither of these last two, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kudinova-Pasternak" authorityYear="1975" box="[1262,1436,1872,1897]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auritocheles">
<emphasis box="[1262,1436,1872,1897]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">C. auritocheles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has lateral spiniform apophyses on the anterior margin of the branchial chamber, while, uniquely, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Norman &amp; Stebbing" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[151,347,1952,1977]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="15" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplicirostris">
<emphasis box="[151,347,1952,1977]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="28">C. simplicirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a long and slender rostral spine, little wider at its base than apically (
<bibRefCitation author="Norman &amp; Stebbing T. R. R." pageId="15" pageNumber="28" pagination="77 - 141" refId="ref11905" refString="Norman A. M. &amp; Stebbing T. R. R. (1886) On the Crustacea Isopoda of the ' Lightning', ' Porcupine' and ' Valorous' Expeditions. Transactions of the Zoological Society of London, 12 (Part IV, No. 1), 77 - 141, Pls 16 - 27." type="journal article" year="1886">Norman &amp; Stebbing 1886</bibRefCitation>
, Pl. 18, Fig. ID).
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="16" pageNumber="29" startId="16.[151,254,1654,1678]" targetBox="[182,1391,196,1623]" targetPageId="16">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1654,1713]" pageId="16" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,1654,1678]" pageId="16" pageNumber="29">FIGURE 9.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Bamber, 2007" authorityName="Bamber" authorityYear="2007" box="[288,554,1655,1678]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="16" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varindex" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[288,554,1655,1678]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="29">Carpoapseudes varindex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[562,613,1655,1678]" pageId="16" pageNumber="29" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
A, male cephalothorax and appendages, lateral; B, outline of cephalon, ventral; C, distal detail of dactylus of cheliped. Scale line = 1 mm for A, B, 0.2 mm for C.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1804,2030]" pageId="16" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName authority="Bamber, 2007" authorityName="Bamber" authorityYear="2007" box="[198,491,1805,1830]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="16" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varindex" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[198,491,1805,1830]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="29">Carpoapseudes varindex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[503,558,1804,1830]" pageId="16" pageNumber="29" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
may be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bacescu" authorityYear="1981" box="[913,1067,1805,1830]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="16" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kudinovae">
<emphasis box="[913,1067,1805,1830]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="29">C. kudinovae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species from the northeast Atlantic to which 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bamber" authorityYear="2007" box="[365,501,1845,1870]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="16" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varindex">
<emphasis box="[365,501,1845,1870]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="29">C. varindex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears closest, in the proportions of pereonites 2 and 3, the lack of anterolateral spiniform apophyses on pereonite 6, the fewer segments in the antennal flagellum and antennular accessory flagellum, fewer setae on the antennal squama, the constriction on the dactylus of the male cheliped, the lack of proximal apophysis on the pereopod 1 basis, more setae on the pereopod 1 exopodite, and in particular the length and setation of the pleopod basis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,258]" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">
According to the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Gu tu, M." box="[505,653,151,178]" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" pagination="87 - 93" refId="ref11251" refString="Gu tu, M. (1996) The description of Spinoapseudes n. g., and amended diagnoses of two genera of Tanaidacea (Crustacea). Revue Roumaine de Biologie, Serie de Biologie Animale, 41 (2), 87 - 93." type="journal article" year="1996">Guṭu (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, the present species would key out to 
<taxonomicName authority="Bacescu, 1987" authorityName="Bacescu" authorityYear="1987" box="[1114,1432,152,178]" class="Malacostraca" family="Apseudidae" genus="Carpoapseudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="romanae">
<emphasis box="[1114,1249,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">C. romanae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bacescu, M." box="[1259,1432,152,178]" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" pagination="19 - 33" refId="ref10860" refString="Bacescu, M. (1987) Abyssal Apseudomorpha (Crustacea, Tanaidacea) of NW Madagascar. Travaux du Museum d'His- toire naturelle &quot; Grigore Antipa &quot;, 29, 19 - 33." type="journal article" year="1987">Bãcescu, 1987</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, owing to the relatively short antennal flagellum (ten segments), but that species has a quite different truncate, although pointed, rostrum (
<bibRefCitation author="Bacescu, M." box="[460,623,232,258]" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" pagination="19 - 33" refId="ref10860" refString="Bacescu, M. (1987) Abyssal Apseudomorpha (Crustacea, Tanaidacea) of NW Madagascar. Travaux du Museum d'His- toire naturelle &quot; Grigore Antipa &quot;, 29, 19 - 33." type="journal article" year="1987">Bãcescu 1987</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[634,725,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,254,1936,1960]" captionTargetBox="[239,1345,186,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-63@9.[217,1357,173,1948]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Carpoapseudes spinigena n.sp., A, labrum; B, right mandible; C left mandible (palp not shown); D, labium; E, maxillule; F, maxilla (most setae of rostral row shown only by their bases); G, maxilliped; H, maxilliped endite, with detail of inner caudo-distal seta. Scale line = 0.3 mm." pageId="17" pageNumber="30">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
